{"id":"gr-qc/0110063","submitter":"J. Ponce de Leon","authors":"J. Ponce de Leon","title":"Does The Force From an Extra Dimension Contradict Physics in 4D?","comments":"Minor addition in the Introduction to match the version to appear in\n  Phys. Lett. B","journal-ref":"Phys.Lett. B523 (2001) 311-316","doi":"10.1016/S0370-2693(01)01349-1","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":null,"abstract":"  We examine the question of whether violation of 4D physics is an inevitable\nconsequence of existence of an extra non-compactified dimension. Recent\ninvestigations in membrane and Kaluza-Klein theory indicate that when the\nmetric of the spacetime is allowed to depend on the extra coordinate, i.e., the\ncilindricity condition is dropped, the equation describing the trajectory of a\nparticle in one lower dimension has an extra force with some abnormal\nproperties. Among them, a force term parallel to the four-velocity of the\nparticle and, what is perhaps more surprising,\n  $u_{\\mu}f^{\\mu} \\neq u^{\\mu}f_{\\mu}$. These properties violate basic concepts\nin 4D physics. In this paper we argue that these abnormal properties are {\\em\nnot} consequence of the extra dimension, but result from the formalism used. We\npropose a new definition for the force, from the extra dimension, which is free\nof any contradictions and consistent with usual 4D physics. We show, using\nwarp-products metrics, that this new definition is also more consistent with\nour physical intuition. The effects of this force could be detected observing\nobjects moving with high speed, near black holes and/or in cosmological\nsituations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 13 Oct 2001 05:56:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 9 Nov 2001 17:10:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-25"}
